Helene D. Marsh Ph.D. (born 8 April 1945) is a scientist who has provided research in the field of Environmental Science, more specifically Zoology and Ecology. The focal point of her research has been on the biology of dugongs, with particular focus in the areas of population ecology, history, reproduction, diet, and movements. She is the Dean of Graduate Research Studies and the Professor of Environmental Science at James Cook University in Queensland, Australia, and also a Distinguished Professor in the College of Marine and Environmental Science. Marsh is also a program leader for the Marine and Tropical Research Science Facility. In 2015 she became a Fellow of both the Australian Academy of Science, and the Australian Academy of Technological Sciences and Engineering.
